<TITLE> Oath taken to thwart war criminals in polls </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec1 (bdnews24.com)  The Sector Commanders' Forum  the generals who marshalled the troops in the war of independence from Pakistan  freedom fighters and general people have taken a vow to see to it that no war criminal is elected in the parliamentary polls. Former army chief retired major general KM Shafiullah, leader of the Sector Commanders' Forum , administered an oath to the people at a rally under the banner, 'Muktojoddha and People' at the Central Shaheed Minar on the occasion of Freedom Fighters' Day on Monday. The oath-takers vowed to continue mounting pressure on authorities to prosecute the war criminals, collaborators of the Pakistan army, anti-liberation forces. They also pledged to prevent war criminals from being elected in the upcoming general and local elections in honour of the martyrs. Presided over by Shafiullah, the rally called upon the people to resist war criminals from winning in the coming election. Shafiullah in his speech, said, "We have to tell all in the far-flung villages so that war criminals cannot win the election." Retired major general CR Datta said, "We must compel the government to bring the war criminals to trial and for this, we need to be united." Workers' Party president Rashed Khan Menon said, "If the force in favour of the liberation war cannot win the election, the history of the liberation war may disappear and Bangladesh will again turn into Pakistan. So, all have to come forward for the victory of the pro-liberation forces." "We want a government that will try war criminals and we want to take this call to the people," observed JSD president Hasanul Huq Inu. Others speaking at the rally were sector commander retired lieutenant colonel Abu Osman Chowdhury, Communist Party president Manzarul Ahsan Khan, president of the Sammilita Sangskritik Jote Nasiruddin Yusuf, , Mahila Parishad president Ayesha Khanam and acting president of 1971 Ghatak-DalaL Nirmul Committee Shahriar Kabir. Retited major general Jamil D Ahsan moderated the rally. bdne
